Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Tuesday!=20
Recently, I=E2=80=99ve noticed a lot of chatter about degrowth, the idea th=
at we need to stop growing, consume less, go back to the way things were. I=
 think it=E2=80=99s one of the dumbest and most dangerous ideas there is, m=
odern Malthusianism.
To be clear: I do not think that we should, as Jane Goodall suggested, get =
rid of ~7 billion people to maybe save the planet. I think we should harnes=
s those peoples=E2=80=99 ideas and efforts to create abundance for even mor=
e people, all without harming the planet.
We should celebrate our progress, not for technology=E2=80=99s sake, but be=
cause it=E2=80=99s taken the work of billions of people over millennia to g=
et here. So today, we=E2=80=99ll do that.=20
Dan told me to make this one much shorter, but I kept it long and full of m=
essy details to express just how complex and improbable progress is.=20
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
I, Exponential
=E2=80=9CThere is no reason to regret that I cannot finish the church. I wi=
ll grow old but others will come after me. What must always be conserved is=
 the spirit of the work, but its life has to depend on the generations it i=
s handed down to and with whom it lives and is incarnated.=E2=80=9D
-Antoni Gaud=C3=AD
There=E2=80=99s a popular complaint, consistently good for thousands of agr=
eeing likes, that because we no longer construct cathedrals, humans just do=
n=E2=80=99t know how to build beautiful things anymore.
=E2=80=9CWe can=E2=80=99t. We don=E2=80=99t know how to do it.=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0
lol. lmao.=C2=A0
The implication that we can=E2=80=99t build beautiful things anymore, that =
we=E2=80=99ve lost our way, that we must reject modernity, is misguided and=
 backwards.=C2=A0
Certainly, no one person, no matter how insanely gifted, knows how to make =
anything like the Duomo. No one person knows how to make anything, even a p=
encil. Collectively, though, we build things that make cathedrals look like=
 simple LEGO sets.=C2=A0
Exponential technology curves are emergent cathedrals to humanity=E2=80=99s=
 collective efforts.=C2=A0
I realize that statement might elicit a =E2=80=9CI am begging tech bros to =
take just one humanities course.=E2=80=9D But hear me out.=C2=A0
What makes exponential technology curves so beautiful to me is how improbab=
le and human they are. They require an against-all-odds brew of ideas, brea=
kthroughs, supply chains, incentives, demand signals, luck, setbacks, dead =
ends, visionaries, hucksters, managers, marketers, markets, research, comme=
rcialization, and je ne sais quoi to continue, yet they do.
I=E2=80=99ll show you what I mean by exploring three exponential technology=
 curves: Moore=E2=80=99s Law, Swanson=E2=80=99s Law, and the Genome Law. Al=
l three required initial sparks of serendipity to even get off the ground, =
after which a multi-generational, global, maestroless orchestra has had to =
play the right notes, or the wrong ones at the right times, for decades on =
end in order for the sparks to turn into curves.=C2=A0
I think it=E2=80=99s easy to forget the human element when we talk about te=
chnology, or something as abstract as an exponential curve, but that=E2=80=
=99s exactly what drives technological progress: human effort. As Robert Zu=
brin put it in The Case for Nukes [ https://substack.com/redirect/945ddec7-=
acb8-499d-bc09-cafd0833bf6c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXe=
pKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]:
The critical thing to understand here is that technological advances are cu=
mulative. We are immeasurably better off today not only because of all the =
other people who are alive now, but because of all of those who lived and c=
ontributed in the past.
The bottom line is this: progress comes from people.
Exponential technology curves emerge from humanity=E2=80=99s collective ins=
atiable desire for more and better, and from the individual efforts of mill=
ions of people to fulfill that desire, often indirectly, in their own way.=
=C2=A0
Do you see how unbelievable these curves are? That they=E2=80=99re the Wond=
ers of the Modern World?=C2=A0
I can tell you=E2=80=99re not with me yet. Hmmmm. What if we just considere=
d the pencil, and worked our way up from there?=C2=A0
I, Pencil
Do you know how to make a pencil?=C2=A0
In 1958, Leonard E. Reed wrote a short letter, I, Pencil [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/b68b31dc-5613-41c6-89f=
8-db526135a1a1?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.g=
b8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], from the perspective of the =
=E2=80=9Cseemingly simple=E2=80=9D tool.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CSimple? Yet not a single person on the face of the earth knows how=
 to make me.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
The pencil narrator writes of the trees that produce his wood, of the truck=
s, ropes, and saws used to harvest and cart the trees, and of the ore, stee=
l, hemp, logging camps, mess halls, and coffee that help produce those truc=
ks, ropes, and saws.=C2=A0
He writes of the millwork and the millworkers, the railroads and their comm=
unications systems, the waxing and kilning that go into his tint, into the =
making of the kiln, the heater, the lighting and power, the =E2=80=9Cbelts,=
 motors, and all the other things a mill requires.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
All of those things fit into three paragraphs; he goes on for another eight=
=2E But I=E2=80=99ll spare you. You get the point:=C2=A0
Actually, millions of human beings have had a hand in my creation, no one o=
f whom even knows more than a very few of the others=E2=80=A6 There isn=E2=
=80=99t a single person in all these millions, including the president of t=
he pencil company, who contributes more than a tiny, infinitesimal bit of k=
now-how.
No one involved in the process knows how to make a pencil, but all contribu=
te to the process, whether they intend to or not.=C2=A0
If that=E2=80=99s true of a pencil, imagine how little of the know-how that=
 goes into a solar panel or semiconductor is contributed by any single pers=
on. It must be measured in nanometers.=C2=A0
I, Exponential
To tell the story of any exponential technology curve from the perspective =
of the curve itself would take more than an essay. It would fill a library.=
 The pencil is but a miniscule input into any one of them, and even the pen=
cil=E2=80=99s story is endlessly deep.=C2=A0
Scaling up to the level of semiconductors, solar panels, and DNA sequencing=
, each infinitely more complex than a pencil, and introducing exponential i=
mprovement into the mix, reveals the man-made miracle that is the exponenti=
al technology curve. I=E2=80=99ll tell their abridged stories on their beha=
lf.=C2=A0=C2=A0
Moore=E2=80=99s Law: Semiconductors
Just as no one person knows how to make a pencil, no one fully understands =
the intricacies behind semiconductors.
Moore=E2=80=99s Law is the most famous of the exponential technology curves=
=2E It states that the number of transi=
stors on an integrated circuit doubles=
 roughly every two years.=C2=A0
When Fairchild Semiconductors=E2=80=99 Gordon Moore wrote the 1965 paper th=
at birthed the law =E2=80=93 the wonderfully named Cramming more components=
 onto integrated circuits [ https://substack.com/redirect/7d027cef-bd68-4d8=
0-a6b2-e5b007e5419f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8=
-6m8ExkRNpU ] =E2=80=93 he only projected out a decade, through 1965.=C2=A0
Famously, though, Moore=E2=80=99s Law has held true through the modern day.=
 Apple=E2=80=99s M1 Ultra chip packs the most transistors on a single comme=
rcial chip =E2=80=93 114 billion =E2=80=93 and Intel recently said it expec=
ts there will be 1 trillion transistors on chips by 2030 [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/182941b1-ad1b-447d-b18=
a-7ea7534906d4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.g=
b8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. When Moore wrote the paper, t=
here were only 50.
Today, some are worried that Moore=E2=80=99s Law is nearing its end. How mu=
ch smaller can we go than 3nm?! Others, including chip god Jim Keller, beli=
eve that we still have a lot of room to run.=C2=A0
Me? If you=E2=80=99re asking me to weigh in on semiconductor manufacturing =
and the limits of known physics, you=E2=80=99ve come to the wrong place. Wh=
at I do know is that betting against Moore=E2=80=99s Law has been a losing =
bet for nearly seven decades.=C2=A0
Moore=E2=80=99s Law has been so consistent that we take it for granted, but=
 its continuation has been nothing short of miraculous. There=E2=80=99s a r=
ich story hidden beneath its curve.=C2=A0
In Chip War [ https://substack.com/redirect/3f01bc72-8138-4c8d-9980-5d58933=
49196?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ],=
 author Chris Miller tells that story. He specifically calls out the breadt=
h of roles that have contributed to maintaining Moore=E2=80=99s Law:=C2=A0
Semiconductors spread across society because companies devised new techniqu=
es to manufacture them by the millions, because hard-charging managers rele=
ntlessly drove down their cost, and because creative entrepreneurs imagined=
 new ways to use them. The making of Moore=E2=80=99s Law is as much a story=
 of manufacturing experts, supply chain specialists, and marketing managers=
 as it is about physicists or electrical engineers.
That=E2=80=99s just one paragraph in a 464-page full of colorful characters=
 and dizzying details. Like the precision achieved by ASML, the crucial Dut=
ch company that makes the EUV lithography machines used to create transisto=
rs. MIT Technology Review explains [ https://substack.com/redirect/9a980069=
-f5cf-4d64-82dd-6c6adb4e0308?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXX=
epKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] the mind-bending precision of ASML=E2=80=99s mirror =
supplier, Zeiss:=C2=A0
These mirrors for ASML would have to be orders of magnitude smoother: if th=
ey were the size of Germany, their biggest imperfections could be less than=
 a millimeter high.=C2=A0
There are many such stories, each of which is a nesting doll of its own sto=
ries. In order for Zeiss to manufacture such smooth EUV mirrors required ce=
ntennial progress in fields like materials science, optical fabrication, me=
trology, ion beam figuring, nuclear research, active optics, vibration isol=
ation, and even computing power =E2=80=93 Moore=E2=80=99s Law =E2=80=93 its=
elf!=C2=A0
I asked Claude to come up with some rough napkin math on how many person-ho=
urs have gone into the creation and continuation of Moore=E2=80=99s Law. It=
 came up with 5 billion over the past 60 years. When I pushed it to include=
 adjacent but necessary industries, we got to 9-11 billion person hours acr=
oss research, engineering, manufacturing, equipment development, materials =
science, computer manufacturing, software and application development, elec=
trical engineering, and investing.
This is an extremely conservative estimate. If you were to take the I, Penc=
il approach, you=E2=80=99d need to include the people who mine the quartzit=
e from which silicon is extracted, and all of the people who make all of th=
e things that support their effort, as just one example. You=E2=80=99d need=
 to include the many people over the centuries before 1959 whose efforts le=
d to the first semiconductor in the first place. You=E2=80=99d have to incl=
ude the teachers who taught the people who drove Moore=E2=80=99s Law forwar=
d, and maybe even the people who taught them. Certainly, you=E2=80=99d need=
 to include the consumers and businesses whose demand for better compute an=
d richer applications pulled the industry forward.=C2=A0
You could play this game ad infinitum, and at the end, all of those person-=
hours turn into a clean chart that looks like this:=C2=A0
There isn=E2=80=99t a single person in all these millions who contributes m=
ore than a tiny, infinitesimal bit to semiconductors=E2=80=99 progress, yet=
 that progress flows so smoothly it=E2=80=99s called a Law.=C2=A0
Swanson=E2=80=99s Law: Solar Panels
No one person knows how to pull electricity from the sun, either, but we do=
 that, too, to the tune of 270 terawatt-hours (TWh) per year.=C2=A0
The solar story introduces another fun dimension to our exploration of expo=
nentials: it=E2=80=99s impossible to pull them apart. One curve propels the=
 next.=C2=A0=C2=A0
Moore=E2=80=99s Law is an important input into Swanson=E2=80=99s Law: the o=
bservation that the price of solar photovoltaic modules tends to drop 20 pe=
rcent for every doubling of cumulative shipped volume.
The first modern solar PV cell was a direct result of research on transisto=
rs. In 1954, a Bell Labs scientist, Darrly Chapin, was trying to figure out=
 how to power remote telephone stations in the tropics. He tried a bunch of=
 things, including selenium solar PV cells, but they were just 0.5% efficie=
nt at converting sunlight into electricity. Not competitive. As luck would =
have it, though, a Bell Labs colleague named Gerald Pearson was doing resea=
rch on silicon p-n junctions in transistors. Pearson suggested that Chapin =
replace the selenium cells with silicon ones, and when he did, silicon PV c=
ells were 2.3% efficient. After further improvements by the Bell Labs scien=
tists, they achieved 6% efficiency by the time Bell Labs announced its =E2=
=80=9CSolar Battery=E2=80=9D in 1954.=C2=A0
Ever since, progress against Moore=E2=80=99s Law has contributed to progres=
s in solar panel price and efficiency through, among other things, thinner =
silicon wafers, precision manufacturing from fabs, advanced materials, and =
computer modeling. Innovation in chips spilled over to cells.=C2=A0
But semiconductors are just one of many, many factors that have driven down=
 the price of solar PV cells.=C2=A0
That Bell Labs anecdote above comes from a phenomenal two-part essay by Con=
struction Physics=E2=80=99 Brian Potter [ https://substack.com/redirect/7ea=
8e25a-7816-4c18-b2de-011e1287c97d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZ=
jmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]: How Did Solar Panels Get So Cheap? [ https://s=
ubstack.com/redirect/3eb1dbb8-6f2e-449f-bbc8-20dbdcbe704f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ=
3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] =C2=A0It=E2=80=99s the =
story behind the curve.
It=E2=80=99s easy to look at a curve like solar=E2=80=99s and simply credit=
 Wright=E2=80=99s Law [ https://substack.com/redirect/ba54d739-30d2-44b9-a8=
67-114d2d4b8e57?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ] and learning curves =E2=80=93 cost declines as a function of cumu=
lative production =E2=80=93 to trust that as we make more of something, we =
can make it more cheaply. In solar=E2=80=99s case, every doubling of cumula=
tive production leads to a 20% decline in price. You can just plug the numb=
ers into a spreadsheet, and voila!=C2=A0
But that approach misses all of the magic.=C2=A0
After the serendipitous encounter at Bell Labs, itself a study worthy of th=
e excellent 422-page The Idea Factory [ https://substack.com/redirect/fb0ab=
f14-9918-41f2-b94b-300be6d3cdb2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjm=
lXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], solar cells struggled to find a market. They wer=
e just too expensive, even for the Coast Guard and Forest Service. Chapin c=
alculated that it would cost $1.5 million to power the average home with so=
lar PV cells.=C2=A0
But in 1957, the Soviets launched Sputnik (powered by heavy, short-lived ba=
tteries). The Space Race was on. By March of the next year, the US launched=
 the first solar powered satellite, Vanguard I.=C2=A0
Over the next 15 years, the US and USSR launched over 1,000 satellites, mor=
e than 95% of which were powered by solar PV cells, which were much lighter=
 than batteries and provided energy nearly as long as the sun shone. As lat=
e as 1974, satellites made up 94% of the solar PV market. The cost fell 300=
% to $100 per watt on the back of satellite demand.=C2=A0
Without perfectly-timed demand from satellites, solar PV might have been DO=
A. I trust I don=E2=80=99t need to remind you to consider all of the work, =
research, and materials that went into getting satellites to space in the f=
irst place as an input into solar=E2=80=99s progress.=C2=A0
But even at $100 per watt, solar wasn=E2=80=99t competitive with other elec=
tricity sources for terrestrial use cases, but an entrepreneur =E2=80=93 El=
liot Berman =E2=80=93 launched a company to change that. When his Solar Pow=
er Corporation failed to raise from venture capitalists, it found an unlike=
ly backer in Exxon. Solar Power Corporation cut costs by =E2=80=9Cusing was=
te silicon wafers from the computer industry=E2=80=9D and using the full wa=
fer instead of cutting off their rounded edges. They made trade-offs =E2=80=
=93 =E2=80=9Ca less efficient, less reliable, but much cheaper solar PV cel=
l=E2=80=9D =E2=80=93 and by 1973, they were able to =E2=80=9Cproduce solar =
PV electricity for $10 per watt, and sell it for $20.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99m getting carried away in the details, I know. This stuff fascina=
tes me. But the show must go on, so I highly suggest you read Potter=E2=80=
=99s posts (Part I [ https://substack.com/redirect/3eb1dbb8-6f2e-449f-bbc8-=
20dbdcbe704f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Exk=
RNpU ] & Part II [ https://substack.com/redirect/1cb9ff3b-eb90-4b20-916a-89=
b01af9be15?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ]) for the full story.=C2=A0
Suffice it to say, it=E2=80=99s a tale of entrepreneurship, government doll=
ars, an international relay race across the US, Japan, Germany, and China, =
individual installation choices, an ecosystem of small businesses formed to=
 finance and install panels, environmentalism, economies of scale, continue=
d R&D, climate goals, and much, much more. The result is that in 70 years, =
solar has gone from the most expensive source of electricity to one of the =
cheapest thanks to the efforts of millions of people.=C2=A0
There isn=E2=80=99t a single person in all these millions who contributes m=
ore than a tiny, infinitesimal bit to solar=E2=80=99s progress, yet that pr=
ogress flows so smoothly it=E2=80=99s called a Law.
The Genome Law: DNA Sequencing
Exponential technology curves even contribute to our knowledge of ourselves=
, even though not one of us knows how to catalog all of the base pairs that=
 make up the DNA in our own bodies.=C2=A0
Over the past couple of years, I=E2=80=99ve spent enough time with Elliot [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/28ffa848-9770-4645-ae4e-2d49246c558c?j=3DeyJ=
1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] and seen enou=
gh techbio pitches that this chart is seared in my brain:=C2=A0=C2=A0
It shows that since 2001, the cost to sequence a full human genome =E2=80=
=93 to read the instructions encoded in the 3.2 billion DNA base pairs insi=
de each person=E2=80=99s body =E2=80=93 has fallen from $100 million to $50=
0. Last September, after the chart was published, Illumina announced that t=
hey can now read a person=E2=80=99s entire genetic code for under $200 [ ht=
tps://substack.com/redirect/da8c4f12-635f-48fe-933d-5d4de40e1b94?j=3DeyJ1Ij=
oiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], one step closer=
 to their stated goal of $100.=C2=A0
The 500,000x decrease in 21 years far outstrips Moore=E2=80=99s Law; since =
2007, the chart looks exponential even though it=E2=80=99s log scale. The G=
enome Law is the observation that the cost to sequence the complete human g=
enome drops by roughly half every year.
Like semiconductors and solar panels, the story of the gene can fill a whol=
e book. It does: Dr. Siddhartha Mukherjee=E2=80=99s excellent The Gene: An =
Intimate History [ https://substack.com/redirect/e0b78750-0521-4bc4-bb9c-05=
cf8c3123a0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ]. You should read it, too.=C2=A0
One thing Mukherjee failed to mention, though, is that Francis Crick was mi=
crodosing acid when he uncovered DNA=E2=80=99s double-helix structure [ htt=
ps://substack.com/redirect/71b7a510-7df9-4c0d-bccb-918be26a342d?j=3DeyJ1Ijo=
iOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], along with James=
 Watson and Rosalind Franklin, in 1953. You can see it in his eyes, right?=
=C2=A0
Nor did Mukherjee mention the role that LSD played in DNA sequencing three =
decades later, when Cetus Corporation biochemist dropped some acid on the d=
rive out to his cabin in Mendocino County, California.=C2=A0
While road tripping, Mullis had a eureka moment where he envisioned a proce=
ss that could copy a single DNA fragment exponentially by heating and cooli=
ng it in cycles and using DNA polymerase enzymes. When he got to the cabin,=
 he worked out the math and science behind his idea, and within a couple ho=
urs, he was confident that polymerase chain reaction (PCR), a way to amplif=
y particular DNA sequences billions of times over, would work.=C2=A0
"What if I had not taken LSD ever; would I have still invented PCR?=E2=80=
=9D Mullis later mused. =E2=80=9CI don't know. I doubt it. I seriously doub=
t it."
Drugs are fun. These anecdotes are fun. But I hope they illustrate a larger=
 point: progress that now seems inevitable was anything but.=C2=A0
Had Swiss chemist Albert Hofmann not accidentally absorbed the LSD he=E2=80=
=99d synthesized when researching compounds derived from ergot through his =
fingertips, we may not understand the human genome today. That he did (and =
then intentionally took a healthy 250 microgram dose to explore further) is=
 one of many little things that had to go just right in order to sequence t=
he genome.=C2=A0
Two years after Mullis invented PCR, the US Department of Energy and Nation=
al Institutes of Health met to discuss sequencing the entire genome. By 198=
8, the National Resource Council Endorsed the idea of the Human Genome Proj=
ect. And by 1990, the Human Genome Project (HGP) kicked off with $200 milli=
on in funding and James Watson at its head. At the core of the Human Genome=
 Project=E2=80=99s process was Mullis=E2=80=99 PCR.=C2=A0
Government funding and coordination drove public and private innovation in =
sequencing technology. In 1998, an upstart competitor named Celera, led by =
now-legendary Craig Venter, entered the race, intending to finish the proje=
ct faster and cheaper using a shotgun sequencing technique. Competition acc=
elerated sequencing, and under political pressure =E2=80=93 a startup upsta=
ging the HGP would have been a black eye =E2=80=93 the HGP and Celera joint=
ly announced a working draft of the human genome in 2000:=C2=A0
By 2003, two years ahead of schedule and for a cost of $3 billion, humans h=
ad succeeded in mapping the human genome. And then the Genome Law started i=
n earnest.=C2=A0
The story of genome sequencing=E2=80=99s cost declines will be familiar now=
=2E=C2=A0
Government funding played a role; in 2004, the US National Human Genome Res=
earch Institute kicked off a grant scheme [ https://substack.com/redirect/6=
37bf227-2365-4376-aa3f-9e9e0b42c230?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNua=
MZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] known as the $100,000 and $1,000 genome progr=
ams, through which they awarded $230 million to 97 research labs and indust=
rial scientists.=C2=A0
Private enterprise played a role, too. Illumina, which now employs nearly 1=
0,000 people working to bring the cost of sequencing down, acquired a Briti=
sh company named Solexa for $600 million in 2007 to expand into next-genera=
tion sequencing. (Even investment bankers have a hand in these exponential =
technology curves!) Illumina integrated the technology that Solexa brought =
to the table into its product line, leading to the development of the widel=
y-used sequencers like the HiSeq and MiSeq series, and more recently, the N=
ovaSeq series.=C2=A0
Look at those machines. Without even considering the really challenging pie=
ces inside, imagine the plastics, touchscreen, and feet pad manufacturers w=
ho provided components. Imagine the printer designers from whom Illumina=E2=
=80=99s industrial designers clearly cribbed notes. I couldn=E2=80=99t do w=
hat any one of them do, could you?=C2=A0
Moore=E2=80=99s Law has clearly played its part =E2=80=93 providing the com=
putational foundation for managing and analyzing the large datasets involve=
d in genomics =E2=80=93 but the Genome Law has primarily been fueled by dom=
ain-specific advancements in biotech and chemistry from scores of academic =
researchers and industry pros, and by massive parallelization. To understan=
d those, you should read Elliot=E2=80=99s excellent piece on Sequencing [ h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/fdbeb1e0-97f9-4e8d-878c-1abb0c99548b?j=3DeyJ1I=
joiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
Today, a number of companies are competing to bring down the cost of sequen=
cing and open up more use cases, which in turn will drive down the cost of =
sequencing. One startup, Ultima Genomics [ https://substack.com/redirect/82=
944c28-d4b7-441d-958b-5491fe91e15e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaM=
ZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], came out of stealth last May with an announce=
ment that it can deliver the $100 genome [ https://substack.com/redirect/c3=
ea673e-4f61-4724-b460-bc2638c78479?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaM=
ZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. That=E2=80=99s promising, but remains to be s=
een. You can be sure, however, that the announcement spurred acceleration a=
mong competitors.=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99m leaving out the work of millions of people across generations, =
from Mendel to metallurgists, each of whom has played a small but important=
 role.=C2=A0
There isn=E2=80=99t a single person in all these millions who contributes m=
ore than a tiny, infinitesimal bit to the progress in DNA sequencing, yet t=
hat progress flows so smoothly it=E2=80=99s called a Law.
When Exponentials Break
You=E2=80=99ll have to excuse me if I=E2=80=99ve gotten a little carried aw=
ay. Reading back what I wrote, I may have made these curves seem a little t=
oo inevitable, a little too Law-like.=C2=A0
They=E2=80=99re not really laws, though. Not every technology improves expo=
nentially, and even curves that start going exponential aren=E2=80=99t guar=
anteed to continue.=C2=A0
Nuclear energy =E2=80=93 both fission and fusion =E2=80=93 provide countere=
xamples.=C2=A0
Fission and Fusion
America first generated commercial power from fission with the opening of t=
he Shippingport plant in 1957. By 1965, nuclear plants generated 3.85 TWh. =
By 1978, just 13 years later, nuclear power generation had grown 75x, reach=
ing 290 TWh, good for a 40% CAGR. Had that growth rate continued for just a=
nother eight years, nuclear would have generated more electricity by 1986 (=
4,180 TWh) than the United States consumed in 2022 (4,082 TWh).=C2=A0
But the growth stopped. Nuclear power generation actually dipped in 1979, t=
he year of the Three Mile Island accident. Three Mile Island often takes th=
e blame for nuclear=E2=80=99s demise, but a confluence of factors =E2=80=93=
 economic, regulatory, and cultural =E2=80=93 killed nuclear=E2=80=99s grow=
th.=C2=A0
Unpacking all of the factors would take an entire newsletter (or podcast se=
ries =F0=9F=91=80), but for now, what=E2=80=99s important to understand is =
that continued exponential growth isn=E2=80=99t inevitable once it=E2=80=99=
s started. It takes will, effort, luck, demand, and a million other little =
things to go right, which makes it all the more incredible when it happens.=
=C2=A0
Fusion has fallen off, too. As Rahul and I discussed in The Fusion Race [ h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/375f4216-8add-42e4-b372-165dd4e6fd78?j=3DeyJ1I=
joiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], =E2=80=9CThe t=
riple product =E2=80=93 of density, temperature, and time =E2=80=93 is the =
figure-of-merit in fusion, and it doubled every 1.8 years from the late 195=
0s through the early 2000s.=E2=80=9D That progress slowed, however, as the =
world=E2=80=99s governments concentrated its resources on the ambitious but=
 glacial ITER project.=C2=A0=C2=A0
But there=E2=80=99s emergent magic in these exponential technology curves, =
and dozens of privately funded startups are filling in where governments le=
ft off and racing to get us back on track. If they do, we=E2=80=99ll shift =
from the more scientific triple product curve to a more commercial fusion p=
ower generation curve, and watch the wonders that unfold when that goes exp=
onential itself.=C2=A0
Zooming up a level, despite the shortcomings in any one particular curve, w=
hat=E2=80=99s remarkable is that all of the curves - technological, cultura=
l, economic - resolve into one big, smooth curve: the world=E2=80=99s GDP h=
as increased over 600x since the dawn of the first millennia.=C2=A0
World GDP is an imperfect measure of progress, but it=E2=80=99s a pretty go=
od one. It represents a better quality of life for more people; World GDP p=
er capita is also increasing exponentially, even as the planet supports mor=
e human life. In fact, as Zubrin pointed out, =E2=80=9CThe GDP/capita has r=
isen as population squared, while the total GDP has risen, not in proportio=
n to the population size, but in proportion to the size of the population c=
ubed!=E2=80=9D The more people working on these curves, the faster they gro=
w.=C2=A0
I think that=E2=80=99s what all of the curves represent at the most fundame=
ntal level: billions of people over millennia trying to make a better life =
for themselves and their families by contributing in the specific way they =
can, and succeeding in aggregate.=C2=A0
But where are the literal cathedrals?=C2=A0
Resurrecting Sagrada Fam=C3=ADlia
Exponential technology curves, and even their direct products, are beautifu=
l but hidden.=C2=A0
Semiconductors are hidden inside of computers. Solar panels are visible but=
 not particularly beautiful. DNA sequencing takes place in a lab.=C2=A0
These things are awesome, but I understand if you don=E2=80=99t think they=
=E2=80=99re as beautiful as the Duomo.=C2=A0
Well, consider the Basilica de la Sagrada Fam=C3=ADlia.=C2=A0
In 1883, a small group of Catholic devotees of Saint Joseph (Josephites) en=
trusted a young Catalan architect, Antoni Gaud=C3=AD, to build them a churc=
h.=C2=A0=C2=A0
Gaud=C3=AD, as anyone who has been to Barcelona will gladly tell you, was a=
 genius. He was also slow and unconventional. As architect Mark Foster Gage=
 writes in a piece for CNN [ https://substack.com/redirect/758731d9-29e6-47=
20-903d-af870b770dc0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa=
8-6m8ExkRNpU ]:=C2=A0
Gaud=C3=AD=E2=80=99s vision of the church was so complex and detailed from =
the start that at no point could it be physically drawn by hand using the t=
ypical scale drawings so common to almost all architectural projects. Inste=
ad, it was almost entirely constructed through the making of large plaster =
models to communicate Gaud=C3=AD=E2=80=99s desires to the army of stonemaso=
ns slowly liberating its form from blocks of local Montju=C3=AFc sandstone.=
=C2=A0
That worked well enough while Gaud=C3=AD was there to oversee the models an=
d the stonemasons, but in 1926, the architect was hit by a tram car. Dresse=
d poorly and with nothing but snacks in his pocket, Gaud=C3=AD was mistaken=
 for a pauper and not given proper care. He died within days.=C2=A0
When Gaud=C3=AD died, 43 years after taking on the project, Sagrada Fam=C3=
=ADlia was only 10-15% completed. He did leave behind sketches, photographs=
, and plaster models that guided builders for the next decade. Those, unfor=
tunately, were destroyed in 1936, during the Spanish Civil War, when revolu=
tionaries burned the sketches and photographs, smashed the models, and dese=
crated Gaud=C3=AD=E2=80=99s tomb.=C2=A0
Over the next four decades, construction snailed along in fits and starts. =
Gage explains that =E2=80=9CEven after nearly a full century of constructio=
n, by 1978 there remained numerous aspects of the project that had still ne=
ver been designed, and even more that nobody knew how to build.=E2=80=9D
=E2=80=9CWe can=E2=80=99t. We don=E2=80=99t know how to do it.=E2=80=9D for=
 real.=C2=A0
In 1979, however, a 22-year-old Kiwi Cambridge grad student, Mark Burry, vi=
sited Sagrada Fam=C3=ADlia and interviewed some of Gaud=C3=AD=E2=80=99s for=
mer apprentices. They showed him the boxes of broken model fragments, and o=
ffered him an internship. Burry got to work trying to reconstruct the mind =
of Antoni Gaud=C3=AD in order to construct the church that lived within.=C2=
=A0
At first, Burry tried to hand-draw the =E2=80=9Ccomplex intersection of wei=
rd shapes, including things like conoids and hyperbolic paraboloids=E2=80=
=9D but he realized that the tool wasn=E2=80=99t up to the task. Gage again=
:=C2=A0
Burry realized as early as 1979 that the only tool that could possibly calc=
ulate, in a reasonable amount of time, the structures, forms, and shapes ne=
eded to solve the remaining mysteries of the Sagrada Fam=C3=ADlia was one r=
elatively new to the consumer world: the computer.
Moore=E2=80=99s Law, baby!=C2=A0
Gage=E2=80=99s piece from which I learned this story is titled How robots s=
aved one of the world=E2=80=99s most unusual cathedrals [ https://substack.=
com/redirect/758731d9-29e6-4720-903d-af870b770dc0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb=
8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. It=E2=80=99s the story of how,=
 after nearly a century of slow progress against one man=E2=80=99s genius d=
esign, technologies built over billions of person-hours by millions of peop=
le are finally bringing Sagrada Fam=C3=ADlia to life.
Burry brought in software used to design airplanes to solve the otherwise-i=
mpossible problem of translating Gaud=C3=AD=E2=80=99s sketches of bone colu=
mns into 3D models.=C2=A0
In order to actually construct the building, Burry and team hooked their co=
mputers up to a relatively new invention, CNC (computer numerically control=
led) machines. CNC machines were themselves a product of a number of techno=
logical advances in computing power, data storage, electronics, motors, mat=
erial science, user interfaces, networking and connectivity, control system=
s, and software designs. All of those curves converged in time for Burry to=
 feed his 3D models into CNC machines that could precisely carve their desi=
gns out of stone.=C2=A0
Today, the team working on Sagrada Fam=C3=ADlia uses a full arsenal of mode=
rn technology, from 3D printers to Lidar laser scans, from sensors to VR he=
adsets. The official architecture blog of the Sagrada Fam=C3=ADlia even put=
 together a short video on the role of technology in the building=E2=80=99s=
 construction:
Sagrada Fam=C3=ADlia is an architectural wonder, maybe the greatest in the =
world. Brunelleschi could not have built it with the tools and labor availa=
ble when he conceived of the Duomo. Architects and builders have struggled =
for 140 years to complete it. Burry and team are now racing to complete it =
by 2026 to mark the centennial of Gaud=C3=AD=E2=80=99s death.=C2=A0
Thanks to the exponential technology curves built by billions of people, an=
d Burry=E2=80=99s application of them, =E2=80=9CWe can. We do know how to d=
o it.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
That just leaves the question of will and economics. One of the reasons we =
don=E2=80=99t build churches and stone buildings like we used to is that th=
ey just don=E2=80=99t make financial sense. The modern Medicis are funding =
modern pursuits, like space travel and longevity.=C2=A0
But there=E2=80=99s cause for hope. Building the next Sagrada Fam=C3=ADlia,=
 and the next, and the next, will get cheaper and faster as the physical wo=
rld hops onto exponential technology curves, and those curves continue to e=
xponentiate. Modeling will get better, robots will get cheaper and better, =
3D printing will get faster and more accurate.=C2=A0
Eventually, we=E2=80=99ll have the machines that can build the machines tha=
t can build Sagrada Familias.=C2=A0
The claim that exponential technology curves are more beautiful than cathed=
rals is a bold one, but I stand by it.=C2=A0
You can=E2=80=99t use cathedrals to make exponential technology curves, but=
 you can use exponential technology curves to make cathedrals. And exponent=
ial technology curves continue to expand our capabilities, so that we can b=
uild even greater cathedrals, literal and metaphorical, as time goes on.=C2=
=A0
Less glibly, we should be able to appreciate the beauty of the past while c=
elebrating the tremendous things humans have accomplished since and working=
 to make the future even better.=C2=A0
To use the same G.K. Chesterton quote that Read did in I, Pencil: =E2=80=9C=
We are perishing for want of wonder, not for want of wonders.=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0
There are wonders all around us. We should wonder at these curves the same =
way we wonder at the ceiling of the Sistine Chapel, not for the technologic=
al progress they represent alone, but because they show us what humans, fro=
m the lumberjack to the Nobel Laureate, are capable of.=C2=A0
Trust the Curves
Let=E2=80=99s wrap this up on a practical note. Exponential technology curv=
es aren=E2=80=99t just beautiful, they=E2=80=99re investible.=C2=A0
A key pillar of Not Boring Capital=E2=80=99s Fund III thesis is that enough=
 of these curves are hitting the right spot that previously impossible or u=
neconomical ideas now pencil out.=C2=A0
Understanding and betting on exponential technology curves is the surest wa=
y for entrepreneurs and investors to see the future. With each doubling in =
performance or halving in price, ideas that lived only in the realm of sci-=
fi [ https://substack.com/redirect/03f2a9f7-a2c0-402b-afaf-7917c2b76df6?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] become =
possible in reality.=C2=A0
We just invested in a company whose =E2=80=9CWhy Now?=E2=80=9D is that they=
=E2=80=99re building at the intersection of two powerful curves that are ab=
out to hit the right point. They=E2=80=99re working on a holy grail idea th=
at others have tried and failed to build, because they tried a little too e=
arly on the curves.=C2=A0
This logic is why many of the best startup ideas can be found in previously=
 overhyped industries. Ideas that were once too early eventually become wel=
l-timed.=C2=A0
One of my favorite examples is Casey Handmer=E2=80=99s Terraform Industries=
, which is using solar to pull CO2 from the air and turn it into natural ga=
s. The company is an explicit bet on solar=E2=80=99s continued price declin=
e [ https://substack.com/redirect/b3dbe8e8-8329-44bd-bbf4-0f7afdba2715?j=3D=
eyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], something=
 that even the experts continue to underestimate by overthinking it, and an=
 effort to bend the curve even faster by creating more demand.=C2=A0=C2=A0
New companies enabled by new spots on the curve, in turn, create more deman=
d, which sends capitalist pheromones throughout the supply chain that entic=
e people, in their own self-interest, to make the breakthroughs and iterati=
ons that keep the curves going. That makes existing companies=E2=80=99 unit=
 economics better, and unlocks newer, wilder ideas.=C2=A0
On the flip side, curves explain why it=E2=80=99s been so hard to create su=
ccessful startups that don=E2=80=99t sit at the edge of the curve. As Pace =
Capital=E2=80=99s Chris Paik explained on Invest Like the Best [ https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/0f0c53d1-df41-4b56-a219-0a1661d1df54?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3=
QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], =E2=80=9COne thing that=
 I think is underexplored is the impact of data transfer speeds as actual w=
hy now reasons for companies existing. Let's look at mobile social networks=
 and the order that they were founded in; Twitter 2006, Instagram 2010, Sna=
pchat 2011, maybe most recently TikTok named Musical.ly in 2014.=E2=80=9D
He argued that the most successful mobile social networks are the ones that=
 were born right when they could take advantage of a new capability unlocke=
d by advances in mobile bandwidth: text, images, short clips, full videos. =
In other words, successful social networks built right at the leading edge =
of Nielsen=E2=80=99s Law, which states that a high-end user=E2=80=99s conne=
ction speed grows by 50% each year.
The flip side was true, too. Paik made the case that Instagram couldn=E2=80=
=99t have been successful if it had come after TikTok, and that companies l=
ike BeReal and Poparazzi struggled because they are =E2=80=9Cnot strictly m=
ore bandwidth consumptive than TikTok.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Getting curve timing right isn=E2=80=99t the only factor that determines wh=
ether a startup will be successful. There are companies that get the timing=
 just right, but fail for a number of reasons: they=E2=80=99re not the righ=
t team, they have the wrong strategy, others build against the same curve t=
hey do but better, their product sucks, whatever. There are companies that =
fail because they think they=E2=80=99re building at the right spot on the c=
urve, but are actually too early. And there are companies that succeed desp=
ite not building at the leading edge of the curve.=C2=A0
But building and investing in technology startups without at least understa=
nding and appreciating exponential technology curves will lead to more hear=
tache and write downs than is necessary.=C2=A0
That said, the crazy ones who ignore the curves are important, too. Jumping=
 in too early and overhyping a technology before it=E2=80=99s technically a=
nd economically rational to do so is one of the many things that keep curve=
s going against the odds. That internet bandwidth curve might look a lot fl=
atter if telecom companies didn=E2=80=99t get too excited and overbuild cap=
acity during the Dot Com Bubble.=C2=A0
It didn=E2=80=99t work out for them, but it worked out for humanity. Even t=
he failures push us forward.=C2=A0
How beautiful is that?
Thanks to Dan [ https://substack.com/redirect/e9089ce2-1dbd-4ee6-a7aa-a1173=
fdf7f39?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
] for editing!
That=E2=80=99s all for today! We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Friday=
 with the Weekly Dose before taking next week=E2=80=99s essay off for Labor=
 Day Weekend.
Thanks for reading,
Packy

