/em></figcaption></figure></div><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-si=
ze: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>The first modern so=
lar PV cell was a direct result of research on transistors. In 1954, a Bell=
 Labs scientist, Darrly Chapin, was trying to figure out how to power remot=
e telephone stations in the tropics. He tried a bunch of things, including =
selenium solar PV cells, but they were just 0.5% efficient at converting su=
nlight into electricity. Not competitive. As luck would have it, though, a =
Bell Labs colleague named Gerald Pearson was doing research on </span><em>s=
ilicon</em><span> p-n junctions in transistors. Pearson suggested that Chap=
in replace the selenium cells with silicon ones, and when he did, silicon P=
V cells were 2.3% efficient. After further improvements by the Bell Labs sc=
ientists, they achieved 6% efficiency by the time Bell Labs announced its &=
#8220;Solar Battery&#8221; in 1954.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(=
64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span=
>Ever since, progress against Moore&#8217;s Law has contributed to progress=
 in solar panel price and efficiency through, among other things, thinner s=
ilicon wafers, precision manufacturing from fabs, advanced materials</span>=
<strong>, </strong><span>and computer modeling</span><strong>. </strong><sp=
an>Innovation in chips spilled over to cells.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"c=
olor: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px=
 0;">But semiconductors are just one of many, many factors that have driven=
 down the price of solar PV cells.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, =
64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>That Be=
ll Labs anecdote above comes from a phenomenal two-part essay by Constructi=
on Physics&#8217; </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/7ea8e25a-=
7816-4c18-b2de-011e1287c97d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXe=
pKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: =
underline;">Brian Potter</a><span>: </span><em><a href=3D"https://substack.=
com/redirect/3eb1dbb8-6f2e-449f-bbc8-20dbdcbe704f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb=
8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, =
64); text-decoration: underline;">How Did Solar Panels Get So Cheap?</a><sp=
an> </span></em><span>&#160;It&#8217;s the story behind the curve.</span></=
p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; m=
argin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>It&#8217;s easy to look at a curve like solar&#82=
17;s and simply credit </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/ba54=
d739-30d2-44b9-a867-114d2d4b8e57?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZj=
mlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decorat=
ion: underline;">Wright&#8217;s Law</a><span> and learning curves &#8211; c=
ost declines as a function of cumulative production &#8211; to trust that a=
s we make more of something, we can make it more cheaply. In solar&#8217;s =
case, every doubling of cumulative production leads to a 20% decline in pri=
ce. You can just plug the numbers into a spreadsheet, and voila!&#160;</spa=
n></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26p=
x; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">But that approach misses all of the magic.&#160;</p=
><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; ma=
rgin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>After the serendipitous encounter at Bell Labs, it=
self a study worthy of the excellent 422-page </span><em><a href=3D"https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/fb0abf14-9918-41f2-b94b-300be6d3cdb2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXA=
wZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rg=
b(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">The Idea Factory</a><span>,</sp=
an></em><span> solar cells struggled to find a market. They were just too e=
xpensive, even for the Coast Guard and Forest Service. Chapin calculated th=
at it would cost $1.5 million to power the average home with solar PV cells=
=2E&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: r=
gb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line=
-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>But in 1957, the Soviets launched=
 Sputnik (powered by heavy, short-lived batteries). The Space Race was on. =
By March of the next year, the US launched the first </span><strong>solar p=
owered satellite</strong><span>, Vanguard I.&#160;</span></p><div class=3D"=
