">CNN</a></em></figcaption></figure></div><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64=
); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">In 1883, a smal=
l group of Catholic devotees of Saint Joseph (Josephites) entrusted a young=
 Catalan architect, Antoni Gaud&#237;, to build them a church.&#160;&#160;<=
/p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; =
margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Gaud&#237;, as anyone who has been to Barcelona =
will gladly tell you, was a genius. He was also slow and unconventional. As=
 architect Mark Foster Gage writes in </span><a href=3D"https://substack.co=
m/redirect/758731d9-29e6-4720-903d-af870b770dc0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J=
5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64=
); text-decoration: underline;">a piece for CNN</a><span>:&#160;</span></p>=
<blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid #51b4e9; margin: 20px 0; paddin=
g: 0;"><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26=
px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;"><em>Gaud&#237;&#8217;s vision o=
f the church was so complex and detailed from the start that at no point co=
uld it be physically drawn by hand using the typical scale drawings so comm=
on to almost all architectural projects. Instead, it was almost entirely co=
nstructed through the making of large plaster models to communicate Gaud&#2=
37;&#8217;s desires to the army of stonemasons slowly liberating its form f=
rom blocks of local Montju&#239;c sandstone.&#160;</em></p></blockquote><p =
style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin=
: 0 0 20px 0;">That worked well enough while Gaud&#237; was there to overse=
e the models and the stonemasons, but in 1926, the architect was hit by a t=
ram car. Dressed poorly and with nothing but snacks in his pocket, Gaud&#23=
7; was mistaken for a pauper and not given proper care. He died within days=
=2E&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64,=20=
64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height=
: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">When Gaud&#237; died, 43 years after taking on=
 the project, Sagrada Fam&#237;lia was only 10-15% completed. He did leave =
behind sketches, photographs, and plaster models that guided builders for t=
he next decade. Those, unfortunately, were destroyed in 1936, during the Sp=
anish Civil War, when revolutionaries burned the sketches and photographs, =
smashed the models, and desecrated Gaud&#237;&#8217;s tomb.&#160;</p><p sty=
le=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0=
 0 20px 0;"><span>Over the next four decades, construction snailed along in=
 fits and starts. Gage explains that &#8220;Even after nearly a full centur=
y of construction, by 1978 there remained numerous aspects of the project t=
hat had still never been designed, and even more that </span><strong>nobody=
 knew how to build</strong><span>.&#8221;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(=
64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">&#822=
0;We can&#8217;t. We don&#8217;t know how to do it.&#8221; for real.&#160;<=
/p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; =
margin: 0 0 20px 0;">In 1979, however, a 22-year-old Kiwi Cambridge grad st=
udent, Mark Burry, visited Sagrada Fam&#237;lia and interviewed some of Gau=
d&#237;&#8217;s former apprentices. They showed him the boxes of broken mod=
el fragments, and offered him an internship. Burry got to work trying to re=
construct the mind of Antoni Gaud&#237; in order to construct the church th=
at lived within.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16=
px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">At first, Burry tried to hand-d=
raw the &#8220;complex intersection of weird shapes, including things like =
conoids and hyperbolic paraboloids&#8221; but he realized that the tool was=
n&#8217;t up to the task. Gage again:&#160;</p><blockquote style=3D"border-=
left: 4px solid #51b4e9; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><p style=3D"color: rg=
b(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; marg=
in-left: 20px;"><em><span>Burry realized as early as 1979 that the only too=
l that could possibly calculate, in a reasonable amount of time, the struct=
ures, forms, and shapes needed to solve the remaining mysteries of the Sagr=
ada Fam&#237;lia was one relatively new to the consumer world:</span><stron=
g> the computer.</strong></em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 6=
4, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Moore&#821=
7;s Law, baby!&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px=
; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Gage&#8217;s piece from whi=
ch I learned this story is titled </span><em><a href=3D"https://substack.co=
m/redirect/758731d9-29e6-4720-903d-af870b770dc0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J=
5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64=
); text-decoration: underline;">How robots saved one of the world&#8217;s m=
ost unusual cathedrals</a></em><span>. It&#8217;s the story of how, after n=
early a century of slow progress against one man&#8217;s genius design, tec=
hnologies built over billions of person-hours by millions of people are fin=
ally bringing Sagrada Fam&#237;lia to life.</span></p><p style=3D"color: rg=
b(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Bur=
ry brought in software used to design airplanes to solve the otherwise-impo=
ssible problem of translating Gaud&#237;&#8217;s sketches of bone columns i=
nto 3D models.&#160;</p><div class=3D"captioned-image-container-static" sty=
