6px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Understanding and bettin=
g on exponential technology curves is the surest way for entrepreneurs and =
investors to see the future. With each doubling in performance or halving i=
n price, </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/03f2a9f7-a2c0-402b=
-afaf-7917c2b76df6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-=
6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline=
;">ideas that lived only in the realm of sci-fi</a><span> become possible i=
n reality.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 1=
6px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">We just invested in a company =
whose &#8220;Why Now?&#8221; is that they&#8217;re building at the intersec=
tion of two powerful curves that are about to hit the right point. They&#82=
17;re working on a holy grail idea that others have tried and failed to bui=
ld, because they tried a little too early on the curves.&#160;</p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;"><span>This logic is why </span><strong>many of the best startup i=
deas can be found in previously overhyped industries. </strong><span>Ideas =
that were once too early eventually become well-timed.&#160;</span></p><p s=
tyle=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin:=
 0 0 20px 0;"><span>One of my favorite examples is Casey Handmer&#8217;s Te=
rraform Industries, which is using solar to pull CO2 from the air and turn =
it into natural gas. The company is an </span><a href=3D"https://substack.c=
om/redirect/b3dbe8e8-8329-44bd-bbf4-0f7afdba2715?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8=
J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 6=
4); text-decoration: underline;">explicit bet on solar&#8217;s continued pr=
ice decline</a><span>, something that even the experts continue to underest=
imate by overthinking it, and an effort to bend the curve even faster by cr=
eating more demand.&#160;&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64=
); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">New companies e=
nabled by new spots on the curve, in turn, create more demand, which sends =
capitalist pheromones throughout the supply chain that entice people, in th=
eir own self-interest, to make the breakthroughs and iterations that keep t=
he curves going. That makes existing companies&#8217; unit economics better=
, and unlocks newer, wilder ideas.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, =
64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>On the =
flip side, curves explain why it&#8217;s been so hard to create successful =
startups that don&#8217;t sit at the edge of the curve. As Pace Capital&#82=
17;s </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/0f0c53d1-df41-4b56-a21=
9-0a1661d1df54?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8E=
xkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">C=
hris Paik explained on Invest Like the Best</a><em>, </em><span>&#8220;One =
thing that I think is underexplored is the </span><strong>impact of data tr=
ansfer speeds as actual why now reasons for companies existing</strong><spa=
n>. Let's look at mobile social networks and the order that they were found=
ed in; Twitter 2006, Instagram 2010, Snapchat 2011, maybe most recently Tik=
Tok named Musical.ly in 2014.&#8221;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 6=
4, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">He argued =
that the most successful mobile social networks are the ones that were born=
 right when they could take advantage of a new capability unlocked by advan=
ces in mobile bandwidth: text, images, short clips, full videos. In other w=
ords, successful social networks built right at the leading edge of Nielsen=
&#8217;s Law, which states that a high-end user&#8217;s connection speed gr=
ows by 50% each year.</p><div class=3D"captioned-image-container-static" st=
